least 11 of 19 galaxies with V circ {\textgreater} 150 km
s-1, including M 101, {NGC} 6946, {IC} 342, and our Galaxy, show
no evidence for a classical bulge. Four may contain small classical
bulges that contribute 5\%-12\% of the light of the galaxy. Only four of
the 19 giant galaxies are ellipticals or have classical bulges that
contribute {\textasciitilde}1/3 of the galaxy light. We conclude that pure-disk galaxies
are far from rare. It is hard to understand how bulgeless galaxies could
form as the quiescent tail of a distribution of merger histories.
Recognition of pseudobulges makes the biggest problem with cold dark
matter galaxy formation more acute: How can hierarchical clustering make
so many giant, pure-disk galaxies with no evidence for merger-built
bulges? Finally, we emphasize that this problem is a strong function of
environment: the Virgo cluster is not a puzzle, because more than 2/3 of
its stellar mass is in merger remnants.

